Next, we investigate whether the effects of prior distributions observed in the Gaussian response model are observed in more realistic computational model fitting. Specifically, we consider an example of fitting a reinforcement learning model in a reward learning task (stochastic reward reversal task) (e.g., Waltmann et al., 2022). In this task, two options (‘A’ and ‘B’) are presented in each trial, and the individual chooses one of them. The outcome (reward or absence of reward) is provided with a probability depending on the choice (see Appendix D.2 for details). The standard reinforcement learning model considered here has two parameters at the individual level: the learning rate, denoted as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
